What does this software do then ?
=================================

	BB is an high quality audio-visual demonstration for your text
terminal. It is portable demo, so you can run it on plenty of operating 
systems and DOS. 

Supports: dos (VGA + MDA), stdio, curses, slang, X11, gpm, linux-console
Sound:  OSS, Sun audio, SGI, DEC Aplha, AIX, HP-UX, DOS (GUS CLASSIC, GUS
        CLASSIC, GUS MAX, GUS ACE, GUS PNP, SB, ESS, PC-buzzer 

This fork adds: macOS (ARM64 / Apple Silicon) with curses display and
CoreAudio sound.


macOS ARM64 port
================

This fork contains changes to build and run BB on macOS with Apple
Silicon (arm64).  Both terminal display (via ncurses) and sound
playback (via CoreAudio) are fully working.

Prerequisites
-------------

  - Xcode Command Line Tools (provides gcc/clang)
  - Homebrew ncurses:  brew install ncurses
  - aalib built from source with curses support (see below)

Building aalib from source
--------------------------

The Homebrew aalib formula does not enable curses, so aalib must be
built manually:

  cd /tmp && mkdir aalib-src && cd aalib-src
  curl -O https://sourceforge.net/projects/aa-project/files/aa-lib/1.4rc5/aalib-1.4.0.tar.gz
  tar xzf aalib-1.4.0.tar.gz
  cd aalib-1.4.0

Edit src/aacurses.c and replace any use of stdscr->_maxx+1 /
stdscr->_maxy+1 with the standard macros COLS / LINES (modern
ncurses treats WINDOW as an opaque struct).

Then build:

  CFLAGS="-Wno-implicit-int -Wno-implicit-function-declaration" \
    ./configure --with-curses-driver --without-x \
    --with-curses-lib="-L/opt/homebrew/opt/ncurses/lib -lncurses" \
    CPPFLAGS="-I/opt/homebrew/opt/ncurses/include"
  make

The static library will be at src/.libs/libaa.a.

Building BB
-----------

The makefile is pre-configured for macOS.  Adjust the AALIB_SRC path
in makefile if you built aalib in a different location, then:

  make                     # builds bb binary
  cd mikunix && make       # builds bb_snd_server

Running
-------

  ./bb

You will be prompted whether to enable music.  The demo runs in your
terminal using the curses driver.

Changes from upstream
---------------------

Build system:
  - makefile: Configured for macOS with Homebrew ncurses paths and
    locally-built aalib.  Suppresses old-C warnings that are errors
    in modern Clang (-Wno-implicit-int, etc).
  - aconfig.h: Hand-written for macOS.  Key settings:
      HAVE_ALLOCA disabled (prevents stack overflow / SIGBUS on
        ARM64 in the fractal zoomer's mkrealloc_table)
      HAVE_USLEEP enabled
      SIZEOF_LONG 8 (64-bit)
      HAVE_SETITIMER disabled (references undeclared variables)

Code fixes for ARM64 / 64-bit / macOS:
  - config.h: __attribute__((regparm(n))) guarded with
    #if defined(__i386__) || defined(__x86_64__) since regparm is
    x86-only.
  - mikunix/virtch.c, mikunix/munitrk.c: #include <malloc.h>
    replaced with <stdlib.h> on __APPLE__ (macOS has no malloc.h).
  - unix.c: Sound server launch changed from system() to
    execvp()/execv() for reliable startup without shell overhead.
  - unix.c: SIGBUS/SIGSEGV crash handler added that writes a
    backtrace to /tmp/bb_crash.log for debugging.

CoreAudio sound driver (new file):
  - mikunix/drv_coreaudio.c: AudioQueue-based driver for macOS.
    Uses 3 rotating buffers with pthread mutex/condvar
    synchronization.  AudioQueueStart is deferred to the first
    Update() call to keep audio in sync with the demo.
  - mikunix/makefile: Added macOS/CoreAudio section with
    -framework AudioToolbox -framework CoreFoundation.
  - mikunix/main_ux.c: Registers drv_coreaudio on __APPLE__.
  - mikunix/mikmod.h: Declares drv_coreaudio extern and banner.

How this all started
====================

   Once upon a time we've (my friend Kamil and I) bought two old
Herculeses as secondary monitors. We didn't know for that time that our
Diamond Stealths 64 cards would become obsolete soon. The next day we
downloaded the logo of Linux Texas Users Group - nice silly penguin
looking like a cowboy! It was so exciting logo ... we decided that we
couldn't live without it and we wanted to see it at boot time as a logo
on our secondary monitors. There was a small problem - Hercules doesn't
support color graphics. So we decided to convert the penguin image to
ascii art using netpbm tools.

   The output was very ugly because the converting algorithm was
absolutly stupid.  During the night I designed a new convertor that
used a font bitmap to creat an aproximation table. The output wasn't
very good since the algorithm wasn't tuned so well. Many months this
small piece of code was waiting on my disc for the day "D". Meanwhile I
started a new project XaoS (a fractal zoomer) with my friend Thomas.
And then I got an idea: Ascii Art Mandelbrots!  I was really impressed
by the result! XaoS was faster, portable and looking much better than
ever before. I found a new way to go ...


AA-Project
==========

                               dT8  8Tb
                              dT 8  8 Tb
                             dT  8  8  Tb
                          <PROJECT><PROJECT>
                           dT    8  8    Tb
                          dT     8  8     Tb
   
Three goals of AA-Project:

  1. Port all important software (like Doom, Second Reality, X windows
     etc..) on AA-lib.

  2. Port AA-lib on all available platforms (mainly ZX-Spectrum and
     Sharp).

  3. Force IBM to start manufacturing MDA cards again.

   AA-project was started by Jan Hubicka. In that times just a few
people knew about it. Then a new demo named BB has been relased to show
the power of AA-lib technology. Now the project is freely available and
anyone can help.

Where to find BB
================

   Just join our mailing list: `aa@horac.ta.jcu.cz'.

   All programs covered under AA-project can be obtained at
`ftp://ftp.ta.jcu.cz://pub/aa'.

   Or just browse our homepage at `http://www.ta.jcu.cz://aa'. A ton of
examples of ascii-art generated by aalib, pointers to other AA-Project
resources etc.

Support us:
===========

   We decided to distribute all of our aa-related programs freely (see
COPYING for details). If you want to help us more (so we could develop 
more such software) send a small amount (or big one ;-) to AA/BB team.
In that case, write us for further instructions...

